narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: the professors are very supportive and the department as a whole puts in a lot of effort to help you succeed.

Weaknesses: the course material was not the most interesting.

Strengths: this course was very well organized. Each lesson was carefully planned. Material was presented in an engaging format. The professor's office hours were very helpful, as were the peer tutors. The exams and psets were reasonable. I felt adequately prepared for all exams and was able to complete all psets with relative ease.
Weaknesses: success in this course seems heavily dependent on instructor. My instructor was excellent, and consequentially, I had a great experience. Another slight weakness is the course moves very quickly, so if you do not grasp material the first time around you might not understand it for the test. Other than that, the course has no major weaknesses.
Strength was my professor. Weakness was the material was not too enganging.

I think a strength of the course was having a good professor, and maybe a weakness was the peer tutors. I guess compared to Math 112, I felt like it was hard to get help when my professor didn't have office hours, because I wasn't able to make most of the peer tutoring times and the ones I did go to didn't feel helpful.
Sometimes too hard but good teacher
Should be better prep for exams, the in class lecture does not prepare a student well enough.
good teaching
The course is very well organized and it provides a lot of useful information and strategies that can be applied across different STEM fields.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes! Even if you are not a STEM major, it presents some very important calculus concepts that might be useful for life.
Only if you need it for a pre-req.

I would recommend this course for anyone who needs to take it. I did not take calculus in high school so all the material was new to me, but I felt I gained a thorough understanding of the material and was able to enjoy the course.
Only if you need it. If you took BC in high school and got a 5, just go to math 120.
Yes, I believe this is the best Calculus course at Yale. Mainly because of the cheat sheet. But also because of the professors.
Sure if they already like and are good at math and did 112
Only if necessary for a major, much of this math does not seem as applicable as calculus I is.
yes

Yes! This is a great course that gives you a strong base in calculus. Brett Smith is a phenomenal lecturer and he makes sure students understand the content. Weekly PSETS and 2 midterms are good to help you pace yourself and check your understanding of the concepts. There are many helpful peer tutor hours, review sessions, and office hours.
